In [Part 1](/guides/world-of-printers-1) we outlined the creation of an information model using a controlled vocabulary.  Let's continue diving deeper into a practical implementation.

There are several components along the data lineage.

|   |   |
|---|---|
| **Data Source** | Serves status and performance data over a specific protocol. |
| **Adapter** | Transforms the information provided by the equipment into a form that can be sent to an Agent. |
| **Agent** | Stores information that it receives from a piece of equipment in an organized manner. Respond to request for information from Applications. |
| **Application** | Software applications that support manufacturing operations. |


```diagram

```

Let's walk through this using our previously created sample model.

```xml
<!-- info model -->
<Devices>
 <Device name="printer1" uuid="18J175305721">
  <DataItems>
   <DataItem category="EVENT" id="avail" type="AVAILABILITY"/>
   <DataItem category="CONDITION" id="system_cond" type="SYSTEM"/>
   <DataItem category="SAMPLE" id="life_odometer" type="POSITION"
          subType="ACTUAL"
          nativeScale="0.001"
          units="MILLIMETER"/>
  </DataItems>
 </Device>
</Devices>
```

### Adapter

An adapter is a software application concerened with:

1. Communicating with the data source using its native protocol.

```diagram

```

2. Transforming source data into something that can be sent to the Agent.

What data are we sending to the Agent?  Let's write some pseudocode to understand the data on both sides of the transformation.

| Data Item | Possible Values |
| --- | --- |
| Availability Event | UNAVAILABLE, AVAILABLE |

```javascript
is_available = net.ping('192.168.1.222')

// since all printing happens on port 9100, 
//  we could enhance our 'availability' test
is_available = net.tcp('192.168.1.222', 9100)

// agent will map 'avail' to the correspnding
//  data item's 'id' attribute
if(is_available)
	agent.send('avail|AVAILABLE')
else
  agent.send('avail|UNAVAILABLE')
```

| Data Item | Possible Values |
| --- | --- |
| System Condition | UNAVAILABLE, NORMAL, WARNING, FAULT |

```javascript
try {
  printer = net.tcp('192.168.1.222', 9100)

  // query printer's status
  response = printer.send('~HQES')

  // parse the source data 
  has_error = response.findError()
  has_warning = response.findWarning()

  if(has_error)
    agent.send('system_cond|FAULT||||')
  else if(has_warning)
    agent.send('system_cond|WARNING||||')
  else
    agent.send('system_cond|NORMAL||||')
}
catch
{
  agent.send('system_cond|UNAVAILABLE||||')
}
```

| Data Item | Possible Values |
| --- | --- |
| Position Sample | UNAVAILABLE, numeric value |

```javascript
try {
  printer = net.tcp('192.168.1.222', 9100)

  // query printer's odometer
  response = printer.send('~HQOD')

  // parse the source data 
  total_meters = response.getMeters()

  agent.send('life_odometer|' + total_meters)
}
catch
{
  agent.send('life_odometer|UNAVAILABLE')
}
```

3. Communicating with the Agent using the [SHDR protocol](https://github.com/mtconnect/cppagent#adapter-agent-protocol-version-17), a simple pipe delimited string transmission.


### Agent

The [reference Agent](https://github.com/mtconnect/cppagent) is the quickest way to stand up a "semantic gateway" for the model we created.

```diagram

```

> A semantic gateway translates between messaging protocols and applies domain-specific definitions. A gateway is characterized by an architectural approach and function and can take many forms in software and/or hardware, but uses broadly accepted specifications to provide the greatest possible interoperability between messages.
{.is-info}



The process of configuring and running the Agent is described in depth [here](https://github.com/mtconnect/cppagent#usage). The current representation is XML and JSON served over HTTP. There are several ways to access the information from the reference Agent:

1. Probe Endpoint - The information model itself.
	`HTTP GET /probe`
    
2. Current Endpoint - Snapshot of the latest observations.
	`HTTP GET /current`

3. Sample Endpoint - Set of timestamped observations.
	`HTTP GET /sample`
  `HTTP Server Push /sample` via `multipart/x-mixed-replace`
  


### Application

An application in the context of MTConnect can be characterized as a manufacturing support system that is able to speak the MTConnect dialect.  Let's illustrate a traditional, non-MTConnect deployment to understand the value.

```diagram

```

In the above, delaying interpretation of proprietary protocols results in increased need for domain expertise throughout the architecture. At scale, the task of adding new or modifying existing devices permeates vertically as well as horizontally. 

Below diagram has the following changes:
- Interpretation of proprietary protocols is moved closer to the data producers.
- Domain experts, in this case thermal printer domain experts, are responsible for creating the information model.
- Thermal printer domain expertise is no longer required by system administrators/developers.
- The meaning and definition of words remains constant across the enterprise.
